Certainly! Here are some possible inclusion and exclusion criteria:

Inclusion criteria:

1. histologically confirmed diagnosis of stage III or IV epithelial ovarian, fallopian tube, or primary peritoneal cancer;

2. disease not deemed surgically curable (stage IV) or residual disease >1 cm (stage III);

3. age ≥18 years;

4. willingness and ability to provide informed consent;

5. planned treatment with platinum and paclitaxel-based chemotherapy as their primary treatment approach;

6. at least one measurable lesion at baseline, as defined by RECIST version 1.1*;

7. liver and renal function tests within normal limits;

8. adequate bone marrow function;

9. Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG) performance status (PS) 0-1.

Exclusion criteria:

1. primary peritoneal cancer with an underlying malignancy other than epithelial ovarian cancer, fallopian tube cancer, or primary peritoneal cancer;

2. previous use of platinum- or taxane-based chemotherapy for ovarian cancer;

3. known or suspected germline BRCA1 or BRCA2 mutations;

4. life expectancy less than 3 months due to cancer or other medical conditions;

5. concurrent participation in another clinical study;

6. pregnancy or breastfeeding;

7. psychosis, severe dementia, or other cognitive dysfunction that would prevent provision of informed consent, or refusal to sign the consent form for any reason;

8. any condition that, in the opinion of the investigator, would impede compliance with study procedures.

These criteria are to be used as a guide to assist with initial planning; however, you may need to modify the criteria depending on the specifics of your study design and population. It's recommended to consult with your clinical research team, including medical professionals, biostatisticians, and regulatory affairs specialists, to ensure the criteria meet the necessary regulatory and scientific requirements.
